      "markdown": "Table 3: Design categories and ideas emerged from the design ideation phase\n\n| Category | Description | Associated PMT Comp. | Design Ideas* |\n| :--: | :--: | :--: | :--: |\n| Assistance | Providing assistance and scaffolding to users in managing their information privacy can enhance their confidence and sense of control. | - Self-Efficacy <br> - Response Efficacy | 1. Introducing \"privacy tutorial\" to help the user understand how to attend to their information privacy in the application. <br> 2 Providing flexible options and making it convenient for users to adjust and customize their privacy settings. <br> 3 Highlighting the available choices and options within the privacy policy to improve user awareness. |\n| Condensing Information | Summarizing the privacy policy and privacy-related information into more relevant and digestible textual formats to reduce information overload | - Response Cost <br> - Response Efficacy | 1. Using FAQs to summarize the privacy policy and discuss other common privacy-related topics. <br> 2 Summarizing the privacy policy using plain language and explanations. |\n| Data \\& Statistics | Presenting privacy-related data and statistics to offer a more concise representation of privacy-related information. | - Perceived Vulnerability <br> - Perceived Severity | 1. Including \"privacy rating\" to convey the level of privacy-related risks associated with downloading the app. <br> 2. Presenting privacy violation cases for similar apps in the category. <br> 3 Indicating the number of users who viewed or used the opt-out options. |\n| Inhibition | Encouraging or mandating the users to attend to privacy before allowing them to use the app features. | - Maladaptive Rewards | 1. Prompting the user to first read the privacy policy when clicking the Get button to download the app. <br> 2. Hiding positive reviews until the privacy policy is read. <br> 3 Reducing the value of the service until the privacy policy is read. <br> 4 Requiring a minimum time spent on the privacy policy before download. |\n| Social Interac- <br> tion | Making users aware of privacy problems in the application through sharing and collaboration. | - Perceived Vulnerability <br> - Perceived Severity <br> - Self-Efficacy | 1. Showing social signals such as privacy-specific user reviews to emphasize privacy concerns raised by other users. <br> 2 Allowing users to contribute to the understanding of privacy policies by providing crowd annotations and comments. |\n| Visualization | Simple and intuitive visualizations can convey complex privacy concepts in a more accessible and engaging manner. | - Perceived Vulnerability <br> - Perceived Severity <br> - Response Cost | 1. Using icons to reduce information overload and aid understanding. <br> 2 Highlighting the risks and threats in the privacy policy and user reviews <br> 2. Using visual cues (color, size, etc.) to indicate the severity. <br> 3 Using comics or fiction to encourage imagining potential privacy risks. |\n\n[^0]respectively) to draw the user's attention. Clicking on the rating takes the user to a page giving more information about the rating (0) in Figure 1). This page gives a brief description of the privacy rating and lists the sensitive processes (individually ranked by risk level) contributing to the rating, such as the permissions accessed by the app, information collected and shared with third parties, or questionable privacy practices in the application.\n\nAt the bottom of the privacy rating page is a section pertaining to cases of privacy violations in similar applications. Each case is presented in a card containing a title, a brief summary of the\nincident, and a link to a relevant article or external source. This section aims to help the user get familiar with how their information privacy could be compromised through relevant real-world incidents and therefore contextualize the presented privacy rating.\n\n### 5.3 Privacy Tutorial\n\nThe features related to configuring the privacy options in an application are often hard to locate and, even when located, difficult for the users to understand the consequences [45]. The privacy tutorial in our design presents users with guidance on how to take\n\n\n[^0]:    1. Ideas emerged from brainstorming and included in our conceptual design\n\n    2 Ideas emerged from brainstorming but not included in the conceptual design due to feasibility or complexity"
